## 5. Implementation
HTML: Structure of forms, dashboard, and admin panel
CSS: Basic styling and table formatting (styles.css)
JavaScript: - Validates registration/login form fields
- Alerts for incorrect input
PHP: - Processes login, borrow, and return
- Uses POST to handle form data securely
MySQL: - Queries to insert and update records
- Joins to fetch student and equipment names in admin panel
## 6. Database Design
Tables: - students(id, name, email, password) - equipment(id, name, type, availability) - borrow_requests(id, student_id, equipment_id, date_borrowed, date_returned, status)
ER Diagram:
- One-to-Many from students to borrow_requests
- One-to-Many from equipment to borrow_requests
Relationships: - borrow_requests.student_id → students.id
- borrow_requests.equipment_id → equipment.id
##7. Testing
Methods: - Manual testing of all forms (registration, login, borrow, return) - Validation of empty fields and correct email format
- Tested status updates in admin panel
Bug fixing: - Fixed PHP form errors
- Solved database foreign key constraint errors
- Resolved availability toggle logic
## 8. Challenges Faced
Challenge 1: Handling foreign key constraints in MySQL
Solution: Created parent tables first and used correct data types
Challenge 2: Maintaining session data for login/logout
Solution: Used PHP sessions with session_start()
Challenge 3: Updating availability after return
Solution: Wrote UPDATE query to mark item as available
